    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>10 Castlenau Villas | Barnes. S.W</placeName>
                    <date>May 3<hi rend="superscript">rd</hi>. 1870</date>
                    <salute>Dear Sir,</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I have taken the liberty of sending for your inspection some drawings, I have lately made of the Pollen of the Geranium and Honeysuckle—<ref target="#foot.f1"/></p>
<p>I noticed that all the pollen bore a marked likeness to oneanother, but that with both specimens, there were one or two exceptions of so remarkable a character, that they might be taken for the Pollen of another plant—</p>
<p>The number of pollen grains in each specimen, were about 30 to 40. The exceptions shown were the only ones of that type.—</p>
<p>Is it possible that the varieties in the character of seedlings, owe their origen to the particular seeds being impregnated with these exceptional pollen.—</p>
<p>It appears probable that as the pollen is the sexual part of the part,<ref target="#foot.f2"/> and any marked peculiarity would be transmitted to the seed impregnated—</p>
<p>For my drawing, I used one of Smith &amp; Becks instrmts and <formula><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>5</mn></mfrac></math></formula> Object glass.<ref target="#foot.f3"/> They are however enlarged about <formula><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></math></formula>.</p>
<p>I remain dear Sir | Your ob<hi rend="superscript">t</hi> St | John Michels <lb resp="#mjhawkins"/></p>
<p rend="left">C. Darwin Esq | F.RS. <lb resp="#mjhawkins"/></p>
<p>P.S.— I can show the pollen at any time. JM.</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The drawings referred to have not been found.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Michels meant to write, ‘part of the plant’.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">Michels refers to <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_4398.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Smith, Beck &amp; Beck</ref>, scientific instrument makers. ‘<formula><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>5</mn></mfrac></math></formula> object glass’ refers to the nominal focal length of the lens used as object glass in the microscope.</note>
        </div>        
            
